# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: futhark-deep
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:futhark-deep/data-parallelism] A data parallel job on an array of *n* elements can be divided equally among all the processors.
[src:futhark-deep/data-parallelism] Let us assume we want to sum all the elements of the given array and the time for a single addition operation is Ta time units.
[src:futhark-deep/data-parallelism] In the case of sequential execution, the time taken by the process will be *n*×Ta time units as it sums up all the elements of an array.
[src:futhark-deep/data-parallelism] On the other hand, if we execute this job as a data parallel job on 4 processors the time taken would reduce to (*n*/4)×Ta + merging overhead time units.
[src:futhark-deep/data-parallelism] Parallel execution results in a speedup of 4 over sequential execution.
[src:futhark-deep/data-parallelism] The locality of data references plays an important part in evaluating the performance of a data parallel programming model.
[src:futhark-deep/data-parallelism] Locality of data depends on the memory accesses performed by the program as well as the size of the cache.
[src:futhark-deep/data-parallelism] Exploitation of the concept of data parallelism started in 1960s with the development of the Solomon machine.
[src:futhark-deep/data-parallelism] The Solomon machine, also called a vector processor, was developed to expedite the performance of mathematical operations by working on a large data array (operating on multiple data in consecutive time steps).
[src:futhark-deep/data-parallelism] Concurrency of data operations was also exploited by operating on multiple data at the same time using a single instruction.
[src:futhark-deep/data-parallelism] These processors were called 'array processors'.
[src:futhark-deep/data-parallelism] In the 1980s, the term was introduced to describe this programming style, which was widely used to program Connection Machines in data parallel languages like C*.
[src:futhark-deep/data-parallelism] Today, data parallelism is best exemplified in graphics processing units (GPUs), which use both the techniques of operating on multiple data in space and time using a single instruction.
[src:futhark-deep/data-parallelism] Most data parallel hardware supports only a fixed number of parallel levels, often only one.
[src:futhark-deep/data-parallelism] This means that within a parallel operation it is not possible to launch more parallel operations recursively, and means that programmers cannot make use of nested hardware parallelism.
[src:futhark-deep/data-parallelism] The programming language NESL was an early effort at implementing a nested data-parallel programming model on flat parallel machines, and in particular introduced the flattening transformation that transforms nested data parallelism to flat data parallelism.
[src:futhark-deep/data-parallelism] This work was continued by other languages such as Data Parallel Haskell and Futhark, although arbitrary nested data parallelism is not widely available in current data-parallel programming languages.
[src:futhark-deep/data-parallelism] In a multiprocessor system executing a single set of instructions (SIMD), data parallelism is achieved when each processor performs the same task on different distributed data.
[src:futhark-deep/data-parallelism] In some situations, a single execution thread controls operations on all the data.
[src:futhark-deep/data-parallelism] In others, different threads control the operation, but they execute the same code.
[src:futhark-deep/data-parallelism] For instance, consider matrix multiplication and addition in a sequential manner as discussed in the example.
[src:futhark-deep/data-parallelism] Below is the sequential pseudo-code for multiplication and addition of two matrices where the result is stored in the matrix *C*.
[src:futhark-deep/data-parallelism] The pseudo-code for multiplication calculates the dot product of two matrices *A*, *B* and stores the result into the output matrix *C*.
[src:futhark-deep/data-parallelism] If the following programs were executed sequentially, the time taken to calculate the result would be of the $O(n^{3})$ (assuming row lengths and column lengths of both matrices are n) and $O(n)$ for multiplication and addition respectively.
[src:futhark-deep/data-parallelism] We can exploit data parallelism in the preceding code to execute it faster as the arithmetic is loop independent.
[src:futhark-deep/data-parallelism] Parallelization of the matrix multiplication code is achieved by using OpenMP.
[src:futhark-deep/data-parallelism] An OpenMP directive, "omp parallel for" instructs the compiler to execute the code in the for loop in parallel.
[src:futhark-deep/data-parallelism] For multiplication, we can divide matrix A and B into blocks along rows and columns respectively.
[src:futhark-deep/data-parallelism] This allows us to calculate every element in matrix C individually thereby making the task parallel.
[src:futhark-deep/data-parallelism] For example: *A[m x n] dot B [n x k]* can be finished in $O(n)$ instead of $O(m*n*k)$ when executed in parallel using *m*k* processors.
[src:futhark-deep/data-parallelism] It can be observed from the example that a lot of processors will be required as the matrix sizes keep on increasing.
[src:futhark-deep/data-parallelism] Keeping the execution time low is the priority but as the matrix size increases, we are faced with other constraints like complexity of such a system and its associated costs.
[src:futhark-deep/data-parallelism] Therefore, constraining the number of processors in the system, we can still apply the same principle and divide the data into bigger chunks to calculate the product of two matrices.
[src:futhark-deep/data-parallelism] For addition of arrays in a data parallel implementation, let's assume a more modest system with two central processing units (CPU) A and B, CPU A could add all elements from the top half of the arrays, while CPU B could add all elements from the bottom half of the arrays.
[src:futhark-deep/data-parallelism] Since the two processors work in parallel, the job of performing array addition would take one half the time of performing the same operation in serial using one CPU alone.
[src:futhark-deep/data-parallelism] In an SPMD system executed on 2 processor system, both CPUs will execute the code.
[src:futhark-deep/data-parallelism] Data parallelism emphasizes the distributed (parallel) nature of the data, as opposed to the processing (task parallelism).
[src:futhark-deep/data-parallelism] Most real programs fall somewhere on a continuum between task parallelism and data parallelism.
[src:futhark-deep/data-parallelism] The process of parallelizing a sequential program can be broken down into four discrete steps.
[src:futhark-deep/data-parallelism] Data and task parallelism, can be simultaneously implemented by combining them together for the same application.
[src:futhark-deep/data-parallelism] This is called Mixed data and task parallelism.
[src:futhark-deep/data-parallelism] Mixed parallelism requires sophisticated scheduling algorithms and software support.
[src:futhark-deep/data-parallelism] It is the best kind of parallelism when communication is slow and number of processors is large.
[src:futhark-deep/data-parallelism] Mixed data and task parallelism has many applications.
[src:futhark-deep/data-parallelism] The data is divided among different sub-circuits and parallelism is achieved with orchestration from the tasks.
[src:futhark-deep/data-parallelism] OpenMP: It's an Application Programming Interface (API) which supports shared memory programming models on multiple platforms of multiprocessor systems.
[src:futhark-deep/data-parallelism] Since version 4.5, OpenMP is also able to target devices other than typical CPUs.
[src:futhark-deep/data-parallelism] It can program FPGAs, DSPs, GPUs and more.
[src:futhark-deep/data-parallelism] It is not confined to GPUs like OpenACC.
[src:futhark-deep/data-parallelism] CUDA and OpenACC: CUDA and OpenACC (respectively) are parallel computing API platforms designed to allow a software engineer to utilize GPUs' computational units for general purpose processing.
[src:futhark-deep/data-parallelism] Threading Building Blocks and RaftLib: Both open source programming environments that enable mixed data/task parallelism in C/C++ environments across heterogeneous resources.
[src:futhark-deep/data-parallelism] Data parallelism finds its applications in a variety of fields ranging from physics, chemistry, biology, material sciences to signal processing.
[src:futhark-deep/data-parallelism] Sciences imply data parallelism for simulating models like molecular dynamics, sequence analysis of genome data and other physical phenomenon.
[src:futhark-deep/data-parallelism] Driving forces in signal processing for data parallelism are video encoding, image and graphics processing, wireless communications to name a few.
[src:futhark-deep/data-parallelism] Data-intensive computing is a class of parallel computing applications which use a data parallel approach to process large volumes of data typically terabytes or petabytes in size and typically referred to as big data.
[src:futhark-deep/data-parallelism] Computing applications that devote most of their execution time to computational requirements are deemed compute-intensive, whereas applications are deemed data-intensive if they require large volumes of data and devote most of their processing time to input/output and manipulation of data.
[src:futhark-deep/futhark-programming-language] Futhark is a language in the ML family, with an indentation-insensitive syntax derived from OCaml, Standard ML, and Haskell.
[src:futhark-deep/futhark-programming-language] The type system is based on a Hindley–Milner type system with a variety of extensions, such as uniqueness types and size-dependent types.
[src:futhark-deep/futhark-programming-language] Futhark is not intended as a general-purpose programming language for writing full applications, but is instead focused on writing *compute kernels* (not always the same as a *GPU kernel*) which are then invoked from applications written in conventional languages.
[src:futhark-deep/futhark-programming-language] Futhark is named after the first six letters of the Runic alphabet.
[src:futhark-deep/futhark-programming-language] The following program computes the dot product of two vectors containing double-precision numbers.
[src:futhark-deep/futhark-programming-language] It can also be equivalently written with explicit type annotations as follows.
[src:futhark-deep/futhark-programming-language] This makes the size-dependent types explicit: this function can only be invoked with two arrays of the same size, and the type checker will reject any program where this cannot be statically determined.
[src:futhark-deep/futhark-programming-language] The following program performs matrix multiplication, using the definition of dot product above.
[src:futhark-deep/futhark-programming-language] This shows how the types enforce that the function is only invoked with matrices of compatible size.
[src:futhark-deep/futhark-programming-language] Also, it is an example of nested data parallelism.
[src:futhark-deep/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] Essentially, a GPGPU pipeline is a kind of parallel processing between one or more GPUs and CPUs, with special accelerated instructions for processing image or other graphic forms of data.
[src:futhark-deep/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] While GPUs operate at lower frequencies, they typically have many times the number of processing elements.
[src:futhark-deep/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] Thus, GPUs can process far more pictures and other graphical data per second than a traditional CPU.
[src:futhark-deep/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] Migrating data into parallel form and then using the GPU to process it can (theoretically) create a large speedup.
[src:futhark-deep/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] GPGPU pipelines were developed at the beginning of the 21st century for graphics processing (e.g. for better shaders).
[src:futhark-deep/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] From the history of supercomputing it is well-known that scientific computing drives the largest concentrations of Computing power in history, listed in the TOP500: the majority today utilize GPUs.
[src:futhark-deep/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] The best-known GPGPUs are Nvidia Tesla that are used for Nvidia DGX, alongside AMD Instinct and Intel Gaudi.
[src:futhark-deep/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] In principle, any arbitrary Boolean function, including addition, multiplication, and other mathematical functions, can be built up from a functionally complete set of logic operators.
[src:futhark-deep/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] In 1987, Conway's Game of Life became one of the first examples of general-purpose computing using an early stream processor called a blitter to invoke a special sequence of logical operations on bit vectors.
[src:futhark-deep/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] General-purpose computing on GPUs became more practical and popular after about 2001, with the advent of both programmable shaders and floating point support on graphics processors.
[src:futhark-deep/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] Notably, problems involving matrices and/or vectors – especially two-, three-, or four-dimensional vectors – were easy to translate to a GPU, which acts with native speed and support on those types.
[src:futhark-deep/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] A significant milestone for GPGPU was the year 2003 when two research groups independently discovered GPU-based approaches for the solution of general linear algebra problems on GPUs that ran faster than on CPUs.
[src:futhark-deep/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] These early efforts to use GPUs as general-purpose processors required reformulating computational problems in terms of graphics primitives, as supported by the two major APIs for graphics processors, OpenGL and Direct3D.
[src:futhark-deep/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] This cumbersome translation was obviated by the advent of general-purpose programming languages and APIs such as Sh/RapidMind, Brook and Accelerator.
[src:futhark-deep/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] These were followed by Nvidia's CUDA, which allowed programmers to ignore the underlying graphical concepts in favor of more common high-performance computing concepts.
[src:futhark-deep/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] Newer, hardware-vendor-independent offerings include Microsoft's DirectCompute and Apple/Khronos Group's OpenCL.
[src:futhark-deep/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] This means that modern GPGPU pipelines can leverage the speed of a GPU without requiring full and explicit conversion of the data to a graphical form.
[src:futhark-deep/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] Mark Harris, the founder of GPGPU.org, claims he coined the term *GPGPU*.
[src:futhark-deep/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] Any language that allows the code running on the CPU to poll a GPU shader for return values, can create a GPGPU framework.
[src:futhark-deep/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] Programming standards for parallel computing include OpenCL (vendor-independent), OpenACC, OpenMP and OpenHMPP.
[src:futhark-deep/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] As of 2016, OpenCL is the dominant open general-purpose GPU computing language, and is an open standard defined by the Khronos Group.
[src:futhark-deep/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] OpenCL provides a cross-platform GPGPU platform that additionally supports data parallel compute on CPUs.
[src:futhark-deep/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] OpenCL is actively supported on Intel, AMD, Nvidia, and ARM platforms.
[src:futhark-deep/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] The Khronos Group has also standardised and implemented SYCL, a higher-level programming model for OpenCL as a single-source domain specific embedded language based on pure C++11.
[src:futhark-deep/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] The dominant proprietary framework is Nvidia CUDA.
[src:futhark-deep/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] Nvidia launched CUDA in 2006, a software development kit (SDK) and application programming interface (API) that allows using the programming language C to code algorithms for execution on GeForce 8 series and later GPUs.
[src:futhark-deep/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] ROCm, launched in 2016, is AMD's open-source response to CUDA.
[src:futhark-deep/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] It is, as of 2022, on par with CUDA with regards to features, and still lacking in consumer support.
[src:futhark-deep/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] OpenVIDIA was developed at University of Toronto between 2003–2005, in collaboration with Nvidia.
[src:futhark-deep/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] Altimesh Hybridizer created by Altimesh compiles Common Intermediate Language to CUDA binaries.
[src:futhark-deep/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] It supports generics and virtual functions.
[src:futhark-deep/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] Debugging and profiling is integrated with Visual Studio and Nsight.
[src:futhark-deep/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] It is available as a Visual Studio extension on Visual Studio Marketplace.
[src:futhark-deep/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] Microsoft introduced the DirectCompute GPU computing API, released with the Direct3D 11 API.
[src:futhark-deep/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] MATLAB supports GPGPU acceleration using the *Parallel Computing Toolbox* and *MATLAB Distributed Computing Server*, and third-party packages like Jacket.
[src:futhark-deep/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] GPGPU processing is also used to simulate Newtonian physics by physics engines, and commercial implementations include Havok Physics, FX and PhysX, both of which are typically used for computer and video games.
[src:futhark-deep/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] C++ Accelerated Massive Parallelism (C++ AMP) is a library that accelerates execution of C++ code by exploiting the data-parallel hardware on GPUs.
[src:futhark-deep/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] Due to a trend of increasing power of mobile GPUs, general-purpose programming became available also on the mobile devices running major mobile operating systems.
[src:futhark-deep/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] Google Android 4.2 enabled running RenderScript code on the mobile device GPU.
[src:futhark-deep/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] RenderScript has since been deprecated in favour of first OpenGL compute shaders and later Vulkan Compute.
[src:futhark-deep/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] OpenCL is available on many Android devices, but is not officially supported by Android.
[src:futhark-deep/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] Apple introduced the proprietary Metal API for iOS applications, able to execute arbitrary code through Apple's GPU compute shaders.
[src:futhark-deep/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] Originally, data was simply passed one-way from a central processing unit (CPU) to a graphics processing unit (GPU), then to a display device.
[src:futhark-deep/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] As time progressed, however, it became valuable for GPUs to store at first simple, then complex structures of data to be passed back to the CPU that analyzed an image, or a set of scientific-data represented as a 2D or 3D format that a video card can understand.
[src:futhark-deep/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] Transferring the portion of the data set to be actively analyzed to that GPU memory in the form of textures or other easily readable GPU forms results in speed increase.
[src:futhark-deep/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] The distinguishing feature of a GPGPU design is the ability to transfer information bidirectionally back from the GPU to the CPU; generally the data throughput in both directions is ideally high, resulting in a multiplier effect on the speed of a specific high-use algorithm.
[src:futhark-deep/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] GPGPU pipelines may improve efficiency on especially large data sets and/or data containing 2D or 3D imagery.
[src:futhark-deep/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] It is used in complex graphics pipelines as well as scientific computing; more so in fields with large data sets like genome mapping, or where two- or three-dimensional analysis is useful – especially at present biomolecule analysis, protein study, and other complex organic chemistry.
[src:futhark-deep/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] An example of such applications is NVIDIA software suite for genome analysis.
[src:futhark-deep/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] Such pipelines can also vastly improve efficiency in image processing and computer vision, among other fields; as well as parallel processing generally.
[src:futhark-deep/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] Some very heavily optimized pipelines have yielded speed increases of several hundred times the original CPU-based pipeline on one high-use task.
[src:futhark-deep/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] A simple example would be a GPU program that collects data about average lighting values as it renders some view from either a camera or a computer graphics program back to the main program on the CPU, so that the CPU can then make adjustments to the overall screen view.
[src:futhark-deep/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] A more advanced example might use edge detection to return both numerical information and a processed image representing outlines to a computer vision program controlling, say, a mobile robot.
[src:futhark-deep/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] GPGPU as a software concept is a type of algorithm, not a piece of equipment.
[src:futhark-deep/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] Specialized equipment designs may, however, even further enhance the efficiency of GPGPU pipelines, which traditionally perform relatively few algorithms on very large amounts of data.
[src:futhark-deep/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] Massively parallelized, gigantic-data-level tasks thus may be parallelized even further via specialized setups such as rack computing (many similar, highly tailored machines built into a *rack*), which adds a third layer – many computing units each using many CPUs to correspond to many GPUs.
[src:futhark-deep/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] Some Bitcoin "miners" used such setups for high-quantity processing.
[src:futhark-deep/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] Insights into the largest such systems in the world has been maintained at the TOP500 supercomputer list.
[src:futhark-deep/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] Historically, CPUs have used hardware-managed caches, but the earlier GPUs only provided software-managed local memories.
[src:futhark-deep/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] However, as GPUs are being increasingly used for general-purpose applications, state-of-the-art GPUs are being designed with hardware-managed multi-level caches which have helped the GPUs to move towards mainstream computing.
[src:futhark-deep/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] For example, GeForce 200 series GT200 architecture GPUs did not feature an L2 cache, the Fermi GPU has 768 KiB last-level cache, the Kepler GPU has 1.5 MiB last-level cache, the Maxwell GPU has 2 MiB last-level cache, and the Pascal GPU has 4 MiB last-level cache.
[src:futhark-deep/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] GPUs have very large register files, which allow them to reduce context-switching latency.
[src:futhark-deep/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] Register file size is also increasing over different GPU generations, e.g., the total register file size on Maxwell (GM200), Pascal and Volta GPUs are 6 MiB, 14 MiB and 20 MiB, respectively.
[src:futhark-deep/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] By comparison, the size of a register file on CPUs is small, typically tens or hundreds of kilobytes.
[src:futhark-deep/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] In essence: almost all GPU workloads are inherently massively-parallel LOAD-COMPUTE-STORE in nature, such as tiled rendering.
[src:futhark-deep/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] Even storing one temporary vector for further recall (LOAD-COMPUTE-STORE-COMPUTE-LOAD-COMPUTE-STORE) is so expensive due to the memory wall problem that it is to be avoided at all costs.
[src:futhark-deep/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] The result is that register file size *has* to increase.
[src:futhark-deep/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] In standard CPUs it is possible to introduce caches (a D-cache) to solve this problem, however these are relativrly so large that they are impractical to introduce in GPUs which would need one per processing element.
[src:futhark-deep/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] ILLIAC IV innovatively solved the problem around 1967 by introducing a local memory per processing element (a PEM): a strategy copied by the Aspex ASP.
[src:futhark-deep/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] Much like how CPUs may elect to implement wider vector instructions in smaller pieces (e.g.
[src:futhark-deep/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] AMD Bulldozer supported the 256-bit AVX instructions by splitting them into two 128-bit operations) to save power and/or chip area, GPU designers also vary the amount of execution units to fit their expected workloads.
[src:futhark-deep/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] On a GPGPU, each of the following resources can vary freely in ratio from the others: FP64 (FMA), FP32 (FMA), FP16 (FMA), Int32 Add, Int32 Mul, RCP/RSQRT.
[src:futhark-deep/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] (An example can be seen in Nvidia's documentation about the execution resources found in each SM of different generation (compute capacity) of GPUs.
[src:futhark-deep/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] It is therefore insufficient to simply qualify a GPU's computational capabilities in terms of FLOPS: FLOPS values should be separately presented for matrix vs non-matrix modes and (T)OPS figures should also be presented for integer operations.
[src:futhark-deep/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] The high performance of GPUs comes at the cost of high power consumption, which under full load is in fact as much power as the rest of the PC system combined.
[src:futhark-deep/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] The maximum power consumption of the Pascal series GPU (Tesla P100) was specified to be 250W.
[src:futhark-deep/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] In terms of raw computing power (FLOPS, TOPS, etc.), GPUs tend to have more performance-per-watt than a typical CPU.
[src:futhark-deep/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] However, it takes a well-written program and a fitting workload to extract most of this power, as most of the time (and power) would otherwise be wasted on local and host memory access.
[src:futhark-deep/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] Before CUDA was published in 2007, GPGPU was "classical" and involved repurposing graphics primitives.
[src:futhark-deep/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] More examples are available in part 4 of *GPU Gems 2*.
[src:futhark-deep/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] Using GPU for numerical linear algebra began at least in 2001.
[src:futhark-deep/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] It had been used for Gauss-Seidel solver, conjugate gradients, etc.
[src:futhark-deep/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] Computer video cards are produced by various vendors, such as Nvidia, AMD.
[src:futhark-deep/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] Cards from such vendors differ on implementing data-format support, such as integer and floating-point formats (32-bit and 64-bit).
[src:futhark-deep/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] Microsoft introduced a *Shader Model* standard, to help rank the various features of graphic cards into a simple Shader Model version number (1.0, 2.0, 3.0, etc.).
[src:futhark-deep/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] Pre-Direct3D 9 video cards only supported paletted or integer color types.
[src:futhark-deep/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] Sometimes another alpha value is added, to be used for transparency.
[src:futhark-deep/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] For early fixed-function or limited programmability graphics (i.e., up to and including Direct3D 8.1-compliant GPUs) this was sufficient because this is also the representation used in displays.
[src:futhark-deep/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] This representation does have certain limitations.
[src:futhark-deep/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] Given sufficient graphics processing power even graphics programmers would like to use better formats, such as floating point data formats, to obtain effects such as high-dynamic-range imaging.
[src:futhark-deep/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] Many GPGPU applications require floating point accuracy, which came with video cards conforming to the Direct3D 9 specification.
[src:futhark-deep/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] Direct3D 9 Shader Model 2.x suggested the support of two precision types: full and partial precision.
[src:futhark-deep/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] Full precision support could either be FP32 or FP24 (floating point 32- or 24-bit per component) or greater, while partial precision was FP16.
[src:futhark-deep/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] ATI's Radeon R300 series of GPUs supported FP24 precision only in the programmable fragment pipeline (although FP32 was supported in the vertex processors) while Nvidia's NV30 series supported both FP16 and FP32; other vendors such as S3 Graphics and XGI supported a mixture of formats up to FP24.
[src:futhark-deep/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] The implementations of floating point on Nvidia GPUs are mostly IEEE compliant; however, this is not true across all vendors.
[src:futhark-deep/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] This has implications for correctness which are considered important to some scientific applications.
[src:futhark-deep/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] While 64-bit floating point values (double precision float) are commonly available on CPUs, these are not universally supported on GPUs.
[src:futhark-deep/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] Some GPU architectures sacrifice IEEE compliance, while others lack double-precision.
[src:futhark-deep/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] Efforts have occurred to emulate double-precision floating point values on GPUs; however, the speed tradeoff negates any benefit to offloading the computing onto the GPU in the first place.
[src:futhark-deep/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] Most operations on the GPU operate in a vectorized fashion: one operation can be performed on up to four values at once.
[src:futhark-deep/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] For example, if one color ⟨R1, G1, B1⟩ is to be modulated by another color ⟨R2, G2, B2⟩, the GPU can produce the resulting color ⟨R1*R2, G1*G2, B1*B2⟩ in one operation.
[src:futhark-deep/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] This functionality is useful in graphics because almost every basic data type is a vector (either 2-, 3-, or 4-dimensional).
[src:futhark-deep/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] Examples include vertices, colors, normal vectors, and texture coordinates.
[src:futhark-deep/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] GPUs are originally designed specifically for graphics and thus are very restrictive in operations and programming.
[src:futhark-deep/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] Due to their design, GPUs are only effective for problems that can be solved using stream processing and the hardware can only be used in certain ways.
[src:futhark-deep/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] In the early GPGPU age, GPUs can only process independent vertices and fragments, but can process many of them in parallel.
[src:futhark-deep/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] This is especially effective when the programmer wants to process many vertices or fragments in the same way.
[src:futhark-deep/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] In this sense, GPUs are stream processors – processors that can operate in parallel by running one kernel on many records in a stream at once.
[src:futhark-deep/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] Programmers would use graphics APIs (OpenGL or Direct3D) to perform general-purpose computation.
[src:futhark-deep/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] With the introduction of the CUDA (Nvidia, 2007) and OpenCL (vendor-independent, 2008) general-purpose computing APIs, in new GPGPU codes it is no longer necessary to map the computation to graphics primitives.
[src:futhark-deep/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] The stream processing nature of GPUs remains valid regardless of the APIs used.
[src:futhark-deep/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] A *stream* is simply a set of records that require similar computation.
[src:futhark-deep/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] *Kernels* are the functions that are applied to each element in the stream.
[src:futhark-deep/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] In the GPUs, *vertices* and *fragments* are the elements in streams and vertex and fragment shaders are the kernels to be run on them.
[src:futhark-deep/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] For each element we can only read from the input, perform operations on it, and write to the output.
[src:futhark-deep/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] It is permissible to have multiple inputs and multiple outputs, but never a piece of memory that is both readable and writable.
[src:futhark-deep/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] Arithmetic intensity is defined as the number of operations performed per word of memory transferred.
[src:futhark-deep/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] It is important for GPGPU applications to have high arithmetic intensity else the memory access latency will limit computational speedup.
[src:futhark-deep/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] Ideal GPGPU applications have large data sets, high parallelism, and minimal dependency between data elements.
[src:futhark-deep/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] In fact, a program can substitute a write only texture for output instead of the framebuffer.
[src:futhark-deep/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] This is done either through render-to-texture (RTT), render-to-backbuffer-copy-to-texture (RTBCTT), or the more recent stream-out.
[src:futhark-deep/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] The most common form for a stream to take in GPGPU is a 2D grid because this fits naturally with the rendering model built into GPUs.
[src:futhark-deep/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] Many computations naturally map into grids: matrix algebra, image processing, physically based simulation, and so on.
[src:futhark-deep/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] Since textures are used as memory, texture lookups are then used as memory reads.
[src:futhark-deep/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] Certain operations can be done automatically by the GPU because of this.
[src:futhark-deep/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] Compute kernels can be thought of as the body of loops.
[src:futhark-deep/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] On the GPU, the programmer only specifies the body of the loop as the kernel and what data to loop over by invoking geometry processing.
[src:futhark-deep/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] For accurate technical information on this topic see Predication_(computer_architecture)#SIMD,_SIMT_and_vector_predication and ILLIAC IV "branching" (the term "predicate mask" did not exist in 1967).
[src:futhark-deep/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] In sequential code it is possible to control the flow of the program using if-then-else statements and various forms of loops.
[src:futhark-deep/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] Such flow control structures have only recently been added to GPUs.
[src:futhark-deep/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] Conditional writes could be performed using a properly crafted series of arithmetic/bit operations, but looping and conditional branching were not possible.
[src:futhark-deep/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] Recent GPUs allow branching, but usually with a performance penalty.
[src:futhark-deep/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] Branching should generally be avoided in inner loops, whether in CPU or GPU code, and various methods, such as static branch resolution, pre-computation, predication, loop splitting, and Z-cull can be used to achieve branching when hardware support does not exist.
[src:futhark-deep/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] The map operation simply applies the given function (the kernel) to every element in the stream.
[src:futhark-deep/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] A simple example is multiplying each value in the stream by a constant (increasing the brightness of an image).
[src:futhark-deep/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] The map operation is simple to implement on the GPU.
[src:futhark-deep/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] The programmer generates a fragment for each pixel on screen and applies a fragment program to each one.
[src:futhark-deep/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] The result stream of the same size is stored in the output buffer.
[src:futhark-deep/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] Some computations require calculating a smaller stream (possibly a stream of only one element) from a larger stream.
[src:futhark-deep/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] This is called a reduction of the stream.
[src:futhark-deep/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] Generally, a reduction can be performed in multiple steps.
[src:futhark-deep/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] The results from the prior step are used as the input for the current step and the range over which the operation is applied is reduced until only one stream element remains.
[src:futhark-deep/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] Stream filtering is essentially a non-uniform reduction.
[src:futhark-deep/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] Filtering involves removing items from the stream based on some criteria.
[src:futhark-deep/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] The scan operation, also termed *parallel prefix sum*, takes in a vector (stream) of data elements and an (arbitrary) associative binary function '+' with an identity element 'i'.
[src:futhark-deep/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] If the input is [a0, a1, a2, a3, ...], an *exclusive scan* produces the output [i, a0, a0 + a1, a0 + a1 + a2, ...], while an *inclusive scan* produces the output [a0, a0 + a1, a0 + a1 + a2, a0 + a1 + a2 + a3, ...] and does not require an identity to exist.
[src:futhark-deep/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] While at first glance the operation may seem inherently serial, efficient parallel scan algorithms are possible and have been implemented on graphics processing units.
[src:futhark-deep/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] The scan operation has uses in e.g., quicksort and sparse matrix-vector multiplication.
[src:futhark-deep/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] The scatter operation is most naturally defined on the vertex processor.
[src:futhark-deep/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] The vertex processor is able to adjust the position of the vertex, which allows the programmer to control where information is deposited on the grid.
[src:futhark-deep/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] Other extensions are also possible, such as controlling how large an area the vertex affects.
[src:futhark-deep/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] The fragment processor cannot perform a direct scatter operation because the location of each fragment on the grid is fixed at the time of the fragment's creation and cannot be altered by the programmer.
[src:futhark-deep/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] However, a logical scatter operation may sometimes be recast or implemented with another gather step.
[src:futhark-deep/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] A scatter implementation would first emit both an output value and an output address.
[src:futhark-deep/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] An immediately following gather operation uses address comparisons to see whether the output value maps to the current output slot.
[src:futhark-deep/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] In dedicated compute kernels, scatter can be performed by indexed writes.
[src:futhark-deep/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] After scatter reorders elements according to a map, gather can restore the order of the elements according to the map scatter used.
[src:futhark-deep/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] In dedicated compute kernels, gather may be performed by indexed reads.
[src:futhark-deep/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] In other shaders, it is performed with texture-lookups.
[src:futhark-deep/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] The sort operation transforms an unordered set of elements into an ordered set of elements.
[src:futhark-deep/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] The most common implementation on GPUs is using radix sort for integer and floating point data and coarse-grained merge sort and fine-grained sorting networks for general comparable data.
[src:futhark-deep/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] The search operation allows the programmer to find a given element within the stream, or possibly find neighbors of a specified element.
[src:futhark-deep/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] Mostly the search method used is binary search on sorted elements.
[src:futhark-deep/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] Nvidia recommended GPUs for this application.
[src:futhark-deep/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] Check with developer or ISV to obtain certification information.
[src:futhark-deep/gpu] GPUs are also increasingly being used for artificial intelligence (AI) processing due to linear algebra acceleration, which is also used extensively in graphics processing.
[src:futhark-deep/gpu] This contrasts with earlier graphics controllers known as video display controllers which had no internal calculation capabilities, or blitters, which performed only basic memory movement operations.
[src:futhark-deep/gpu] The modern GPU emerged during the 1990s, adding the ability to perform operations like drawing lines and text without CPU help, and later adding 3D functionality.
[src:futhark-deep/gpu] Graphics functions are generally independent and this lends these tasks to being implemented on separate calculation engines.
[src:futhark-deep/gpu] Modern GPUs include hundreds, or thousands, of calculation units.
[src:futhark-deep/gpu] This made them useful for non-graphic calculations involving embarrassingly parallel problems due to their parallel structure.
[src:futhark-deep/gpu] The ability of GPUs to rapidly perform vast numbers of calculations has led to their adoption in diverse fields including artificial intelligence (AI) where they excel at handling data-intensive and computationally demanding tasks.
[src:futhark-deep/gpu] Other non-graphical uses include the training of neural networks and cryptocurrency mining.
[src:futhark-deep/gpu] Many companies have produced GPUs under a number of brand names.
[src:futhark-deep/gpu] In 2009, Intel, Nvidia, and AMD/ATI were the market share leaders, with 49.4%, 27.8%, and 20.6% market share respectively.
[src:futhark-deep/gpu] In addition, Matrox while originally producing custom solutions, now customizes GPUs from Intel and AMD for workstation usage.
[src:futhark-deep/gpu] Chinese companies such as Jingjia Micro have also produced GPUs for the domestic market although in terms of worldwide sales, they lag behind market leaders.
[src:futhark-deep/gpu] Several factors of GPU construction affect the performance of the card for real-time rendering, such as the size of the connector pathways in the semiconductor device fabrication, the clock signal frequency, and the number and size of various on-chip memory caches.
[src:futhark-deep/gpu] GPU performance is typically measured in floating point operations per second (FLOPS); Modern GPUs typically deliver performance measured in teraflops (TFLOPS).
[src:futhark-deep/gpu] This is an estimated performance measure, and should not be treated as fact, as other factors can affect actual performance.
[src:futhark-deep/gpu] Modern GPUs also include dedicated hardware blocks for ray tracing, video encoding, and AI acceleration.
[src:futhark-deep/gpu] In personal computers, there are two main forms of GPUs: dedicated graphics (also called discrete graphics) and integrated graphics (also called shared graphics solutions, integrated graphics processors (IGP), or unified memory architecture (UMA).
[src:futhark-deep/gpu] Technologies such as Scalable Link Interface (SLI), NVLink, and CrossFire allow multiple GPUs to draw images simultaneously for a single screen, increasing the processing power available for graphics.
[src:futhark-deep/gpu] These technologies, however, are increasingly uncommon; most games do not fully use multiple GPUs, as most users cannot afford them.
[src:futhark-deep/gpu] Because GPU computations are memory-intensive, integrated processing may compete with the CPU for relatively slow system RAM, as it has minimal or no dedicated video memory.
[src:futhark-deep/gpu] IGPUs use system memory with bandwidth up to a current maximum of 128 gigabytes per second, whereas a discrete graphics card may have a bandwidth of more than 1000 gigabytes per second between its video random access memory (VRAM) and GPU core.
[src:futhark-deep/gpu] This memory bus bandwidth can limit the performance of the IGPU, though multi-channel memory can mitigate this deficiency.
[src:futhark-deep/gpu] On systems with "Unified Memory Architecture" (UMA), including modern AMD processors with integrated graphics, modern Intel processors with integrated graphics, Apple processors, and modern consoles, the CPU cores and the GPU block share the same pool of RAM and memory address space.
[src:futhark-deep/gpu] It is common to use a general purpose graphics processing unit (GPGPU) as a modified form of stream processor or a vector processor, running compute kernels.
[src:futhark-deep/gpu] This turns the massive computational power of a modern graphics accelerator's shader pipeline into general-purpose computing power.
[src:futhark-deep/gpu] In certain applications requiring massive vector operations, this can yield several orders of magnitude higher performance than a conventional CPU.
[src:futhark-deep/gpu] The two largest discrete GPU designers, AMD and Nvidia, are pursuing this approach with an array of applications.
[src:futhark-deep/gpu] Nvidia and AMD collaborated with Stanford University to create a GPU-based client for the Folding@home distributed computing project for protein folding calculations.
[src:futhark-deep/gpu] In certain circumstances, the GPU calculates forty times faster than the CPUs traditionally used by such applications.
[src:futhark-deep/gpu] GPU-based high performance computers play a significant role in large-scale modelling.
[src:futhark-deep/gpu] Three of the ten most powerful supercomputers in the world take advantage of GPU acceleration.
[src:futhark-deep/gpu] Since 2005 there has been interest in using the performance offered by GPUs for evolutionary computation in general, and for accelerating the fitness evaluation in genetic programming in particular.
[src:futhark-deep/gpu] Most approaches compile linear or tree programs on the host PC and transfer the executable to the GPU to be run.
[src:futhark-deep/gpu] Typically a performance advantage is only obtained by running the single active program simultaneously on many example problems in parallel, using the GPU's single instruction, multiple data (SIMD) architecture.
[src:futhark-deep/gpu] Substantial acceleration can also be obtained by not compiling the programs, and instead transferring them to the GPU, to be interpreted there.
[src:futhark-deep/gpu] A GPU can be attached to some external bus of a notebook.
[src:futhark-deep/gpu] PCI Express is the only bus used for this purpose.
[src:futhark-deep/gpu] The port may be, for example, an ExpressCard or mPCIe port (PCIe ×1, up to 5 or 2.5 gigabits per second respectively), a Thunderbolt 1, 2, or 3 port (PCIe ×4, up to 10, 20, or 40 gigabits per second respectively), a USB4 port with Thunderbolt compatibility, or an OCuLink port.
[src:futhark-deep/gpu] Those ports are only available on certain notebook systems. eGPU enclosures include their own power supply (PSU), because powerful GPUs can consume hundreds of watts.
[src:futhark-deep/gpu] Dedicated 3D graphics hardware dates back to graphic terminals such as the Adage AGT-30 from 1967 with analog matrix processors.
[src:futhark-deep/gpu] In 1969 Evans & Sutherland (E&S) introduced the Line Drawing System-1 (LDS-1), which was the first all-digital system to provide matrix multiplication.
[src:futhark-deep/gpu] Also in 1969, the low-cost graphics terminal IMLAC PDS-1 was introduced.
[src:futhark-deep/gpu] It later saw use as an early 3D gaming machine with the likes of Maze War.
[src:futhark-deep/gpu] In the 1970s, the term "GPU" originally stood for graphics processor unit and described a programmable processing unit working independently from the CPU that was responsible for graphics manipulation and output.
[src:futhark-deep/gpu] In professional hardware, in 1972 PLATO IV system becomes operational at the University of Illinois Urbana-Champaign.
[src:futhark-deep/gpu] Between around 1973 and 1978, several networked multiplayer wireframe 3D games are implemented and popularized by users of the system.
[src:futhark-deep/gpu] Also in 1972, the E&S Continuous Tone 1 (CT1) "Watkins box" system (consisting of an E&S LDS-2 and Shaded Picture System) is delivered to Case Western Reserve University.
[src:futhark-deep/gpu] It offered the first real-time Gouraud shading.
[src:futhark-deep/gpu] In 1975, a joint effort between Evans & Sutherland Computer Corporation and the University of Utah's computer graphics department results in the first ever MOSFET video framebuffer, capable of color and smooth shading.
[src:futhark-deep/gpu] E&S Continuous Tone 3 (CT3) system was delivered in 1977 to Lufthansa for pilot training using computer simulation.
[src:futhark-deep/gpu] It was the first graphics system capable of real-time texture mapping.
[src:futhark-deep/gpu] Ikonas made graphics systems with 8- and 24-bit graphics and 3D acceleration in the late 70s.
[src:futhark-deep/gpu] Arcade system boards have used specialized 2D graphics circuits since the 1970s.
[src:futhark-deep/gpu] In early video game hardware, RAM for frame buffers was expensive, so video chips composited data together as the display was being scanned out on the monitor.
[src:futhark-deep/gpu] A specialized barrel shifter circuit helped the CPU animate the framebuffer graphics for various 1970s arcade video games from Midway and Taito, such as *Gun Fight* (1975), *Sea Wolf* (1976), and *Space Invaders* (1978).
[src:futhark-deep/gpu] The Namco Galaxian arcade system in 1979 used specialized graphics hardware that supported RGB color, multi-colored sprites, and tilemap backgrounds.
[src:futhark-deep/gpu] The Galaxian hardware was widely used during the golden age of arcade video games, by game companies such as Namco, Centuri, Gremlin, Irem, Konami, Midway, Nichibutsu, Sega, and Taito.
[src:futhark-deep/gpu] The Atari 2600 in 1977 used a video shifter called the Television Interface Adaptor.
[src:futhark-deep/gpu] Atari 8-bit computers (1979) had ANTIC, a video processor which interpreted instructions describing a "display list"—the way the scan lines map to specific bitmapped or character modes and where the memory is stored (so there did not need to be a contiguous frame buffer).
[src:futhark-deep/gpu] 6502 machine code subroutines could be triggered on scan lines by setting a bit on a display list instruction.
[src:futhark-deep/gpu] ANTIC also supported smooth vertical and horizontal scrolling independent of the CPU.
[src:futhark-deep/gpu] In the 1980s significant advancements were made in professional 3D graphics hardware.
[src:futhark-deep/gpu] Perhaps most impactful was the 1981 development of the Geometry Engine, a VLSI vector processor ASIC designed by Jim Clark and Marc Hannah at Stanford University.
[src:futhark-deep/gpu] This processor is the forerunner of modern tensor cores and other similar processors marketed for graphics and AI.
[src:futhark-deep/gpu] The Geometry Engine went on to be used in Silicon Graphics workstations for many years.
[src:futhark-deep/gpu] Silicon Graphics's first product, shipped in November 1983, was the IRIS 1000, a terminal with hardware-accelerated 3D graphics based on the Geometry Engine.
[src:futhark-deep/gpu] The Geometry Engine was capable of approximately 6 million operations per second.
[src:futhark-deep/gpu] The 1981 NEC μPD7220 was the first implementation of a personal computer graphics display processor as a single large-scale integration (LSI) integrated circuit chip.
[src:futhark-deep/gpu] This enabled the design of low-cost, high-performance video graphics cards such as those from Number Nine Visual Technology.
[src:futhark-deep/gpu] It became the best-known GPU until the mid-1980s.
[src:futhark-deep/gpu] It was the first fully integrated VLSI (very large-scale integration) metal–oxide–semiconductor (NMOS) graphics display processor for PCs, supported up to 1024×1024 resolution, and laid the foundations for the PC graphics market.
[src:futhark-deep/gpu] It was used in a number of graphics cards and was licensed for clones such as the Intel 82720, the first of Intel's graphics processing units.
[src:futhark-deep/gpu] The Williams Electronics arcade games *Robotron: 2084*, *Joust*, *Sinistar*, and *Bubbles*, all released in 1982, contain custom blitter chips for operating on 16-color bitmaps.
[src:futhark-deep/gpu] In 1984, Hitachi released the ARTC HD63484, the first major CMOS graphics processor for personal computers.
[src:futhark-deep/gpu] The ARTC could display up to 4K resolution when in monochrome mode.
[src:futhark-deep/gpu] It was used in a number of graphics cards and terminals during the late 1980s.
[src:futhark-deep/gpu] In 1985, the Amiga was released with a custom graphics chip called Agnus including a blitter for bitmap manipulation, line drawing, and area fill.
[src:futhark-deep/gpu] It also included a coprocessor with its own simple instruction set, that was capable of manipulating graphics hardware registers in sync with the video beam (e.g. for per-scanline palette switches, sprite multiplexing, and hardware windowing), or driving the blitter.
[src:futhark-deep/gpu] Also in 1985, IBM released the Professional Graphics Controller, designed by later to be Nvidia co-founder Curtis Priem, which was a rudimentary 3D card with 640 × 480 256-color graphics which used a dedicated CPU to draw graphics independently of the main system.
[src:futhark-deep/gpu] It was used as the basis of cards by a number of makers (including Matrox) and its analog RGB signaling led directly to the VGA video standard.
[src:futhark-deep/gpu] Priem later in the 80s worked on the influential Sun Microsystems GX (also known as cgsix) accelerated 2D graphics card.
[src:futhark-deep/gpu] In 1986, Texas Instruments released the TMS34010, the first fully programmable graphics processor.
[src:futhark-deep/gpu] It could run general-purpose code but also had a graphics-oriented instruction set.
[src:futhark-deep/gpu] During 1990–1992, this chip became the basis of the Texas Instruments Graphics Architecture ("TIGA") Windows accelerator cards.
[src:futhark-deep/gpu] Following in 1987, the IBM 8514 graphics system was released.
[src:futhark-deep/gpu] It was one of the first video cards for IBM PC compatibles that implemented fixed-function 2D primitives in electronic hardware.
[src:futhark-deep/gpu] Sharp's X68000, released in 1987, used a custom graphics chipset with a 65,536 color palette and hardware support for sprites, scrolling, and multiple playfields.
[src:futhark-deep/gpu] It served as a development machine for Capcom's CP System arcade board.
[src:futhark-deep/gpu] Fujitsu's FM Towns computer, released in 1989, had support for a 16,777,216 color palette.
[src:futhark-deep/gpu] For context, IBM also introduced its Video Graphics Array (VGA) display system in 1987, with a maximum resolution of 640 × 480 pixels.
[src:futhark-deep/gpu] Unlike 8514/A, VGA had no hardware acceleration features.
[src:futhark-deep/gpu] In November 1988, NEC Home Electronics announced its creation of the Video Electronics Standards Association (VESA) to develop and promote a Super VGA (SVGA) computer display standard as a successor to VGA.
[src:futhark-deep/gpu] Super VGA enabled graphics display resolutions up to 800 × 600 pixels, a 56% increase.
[src:futhark-deep/gpu] In 1988 SGI sold IRIS workstation graphics with 10-12 Geometry Engines and introduced the IrisVision add-in board for IBM MicroChannel bus (RS/6000) based on the Geometry Engine as well.
[src:futhark-deep/gpu] In 1988 as well, the first dedicated polygonal 3D graphics boards in arcade machines were introduced with the Namco System 21 and Taito Air System.
[src:futhark-deep/gpu] The 1990s again saw considerable advancements in professional workstation 3D graphics hardware from Sun Microsystems, SGI, and others.
[src:futhark-deep/gpu] The introduction of OpenGL by SGI in 1992 paved the way for standard hardware-independent 3D programming interfaces.
[src:futhark-deep/gpu] However, by the mid and late 90s, professional hardware was being slowly eclipsed by consumer products which offered similar or even better performance, especially in regards to texture mapping, at a lower cost and on platforms familiar to end users.
[src:futhark-deep/gpu] In 1991, S3 Graphics introduced the *S3 86C911*, which its designers named after the Porsche 911 as an indication of the performance increase it promised.
[src:futhark-deep/gpu] The 86C911 spawned a variety of imitators: by 1995, all major PC graphics chip makers had added 2D acceleration support to their chips.
[src:futhark-deep/gpu] Fixed-function *Windows accelerators* surpassed expensive general-purpose graphics coprocessors in Windows performance, and such coprocessors faded from the PC market.
[src:futhark-deep/gpu] In the early- and mid-1990s, real-time 3D graphics became increasingly common in arcade, computer, and console games, which led to increasing public demand for hardware-accelerated 3D graphics.
[src:futhark-deep/gpu] Early examples of mass-market 3D graphics hardware can be found in arcade system boards such as the Sega Model 1, Namco System 22, and Sega Model 2, and the fifth-generation video game consoles such as the Saturn, PlayStation, and Nintendo 64.
[src:futhark-deep/gpu] Arcade systems such as the Sega Model 2 and SGI Onyx-based Namco Magic Edge Hornet Simulator in 1993 were capable of hardware T&L (transform, clipping, and lighting) years before appearing in consumer graphics cards.
[src:futhark-deep/gpu] In 1994, Sony used the term GPU (with the meaning graphics processing unit) in reference to the PlayStation console's Toshiba-designed Sony GPU.
[src:futhark-deep/gpu] Another early example is the Super FX chip, a RISC-based on-cartridge graphics chip used in some SNES games, notably *Doom* and *Star Fox*.
[src:futhark-deep/gpu] Some systems used DSPs to accelerate transformations.
[src:futhark-deep/gpu] Fujitsu, which worked on the Sega Model 2 arcade system, began working on integrating T&L into a single LSI solution for use in home computers in 1995; the Fujitsu Pinolite, the first 3D geometry processor for personal computers, announced in 1997.
[src:futhark-deep/gpu] The first hardware T&L GPU on home video game consoles was the Nintendo 64's Reality Coprocessor, released in 1996.
[src:futhark-deep/gpu] In 1997, Mitsubishi released the 3Dpro/2MP, a GPU capable of transformation and lighting, for workstations and Windows NT desktops; ATi used it for its FireGL 4000 graphics card, released in 1997.
[src:futhark-deep/gpu] The term "GPU" was coined by Sony in reference to the 32-bit Sony GPU (designed by Toshiba) in the PlayStation video game console, released in 1994.
[src:futhark-deep/gpu] Pixel shading is often used for bump mapping, which adds texture to make an object look shiny, dull, rough, or even round or extruded.
[src:futhark-deep/gpu] With the introduction of the Nvidia GeForce 8 series and new generic stream processing units, GPUs became more generalized computing devices.
[src:futhark-deep/gpu] GPGPUs were the precursors to what is now called a compute shader (e.g.
[src:futhark-deep/gpu] CUDA, OpenCL, DirectCompute) and actually abused the hardware to a degree by treating the data passed to algorithms as texture maps and executing algorithms by drawing a triangle or quad with an appropriate pixel shader.
[src:futhark-deep/gpu] This entails some overheads since units like the scan converter are involved where they are not needed (nor are triangle manipulations even a concern—except to invoke the pixel shader).
[src:futhark-deep/gpu] Nvidia's CUDA platform, first introduced in 2007, was the earliest widely adopted programming model for GPU computing.
[src:futhark-deep/gpu] OpenCL is an open standard defined by the Khronos Group that allows for the development of code for both GPUs and CPUs with an emphasis on portability.
[src:futhark-deep/gpu] OpenCL solutions are supported by Intel, AMD, Nvidia, and ARM, and according to a report in 2011 by Evans Data, OpenCL had become the second most popular HPC tool.
[src:futhark-deep/gpu] In 2010, Nvidia partnered with Audi to power their cars' dashboards, using the Tegra GPU to provide increased functionality to cars' navigation and entertainment systems.
[src:futhark-deep/gpu] Advances in GPU technology in cars helped advance self-driving technology.
[src:futhark-deep/gpu] AMD's Radeon HD 6000 series cards were released in 2010, and in 2011 AMD released its 6000M Series discrete GPUs for mobile devices.
[src:futhark-deep/gpu] The Kepler line of graphics cards by Nvidia were released in 2012 and were used in the Nvidia 600 and 700 series cards.
[src:futhark-deep/gpu] A feature in this GPU microarchitecture included GPU boost, a technology that adjusts the clock-speed of a video card to increase or decrease according to its power draw.
[src:futhark-deep/gpu] Kepler also introduced NVENC video encoding acceleration technology.
[src:futhark-deep/gpu] The PS4 and Xbox One were released in 2013; they both used GPUs based on AMD's Radeon HD 7850 and 7790.
[src:futhark-deep/gpu] Nvidia's Kepler line of GPUs was followed by the Maxwell line, manufactured on the same process.
[src:futhark-deep/gpu] Nvidia's 28 nm chips were manufactured by TSMC in Taiwan using the 28 nm process.
[src:futhark-deep/gpu] Compared to the 40 nm technology from the past, this manufacturing process allowed a 20 percent boost in performance while drawing less power.
[src:futhark-deep/gpu] Virtual reality headsets have high system requirements; manufacturers recommended the GTX 970 and the R9 290X or better at the time of their release.
[src:futhark-deep/gpu] Cards based on the Pascal microarchitecture were released in 2016.
[src:futhark-deep/gpu] The GeForce 10 series of cards are of this generation of graphics cards.
[src:futhark-deep/gpu] They are made using the 16 nm manufacturing process which improves upon previous microarchitectures.
[src:futhark-deep/gpu] In 2018, Nvidia launched the RTX 20 series GPUs that added ray tracing cores to GPUs, allowing real time ray tracing to be performant on mass market hardware.
[src:futhark-deep/gpu] Polaris 11 and Polaris 10 GPUs from AMD are fabricated by a 14 nm process.
[src:futhark-deep/gpu] Their release resulted in a substantial increase in the performance per watt of AMD video cards.
[src:futhark-deep/gpu] AMD also released the Vega GPU series for the high end market as a competitor to Nvidia's high end Pascal cards, also featuring HBM2 like the Titan V.
[src:futhark-deep/gpu] In 2019, AMD released the successor to their Graphics Core Next (GCN) microarchitecture/instruction set.
[src:futhark-deep/gpu] Dubbed RDNA, the first product featuring it was the Radeon RX 5000 series of video cards.
[src:futhark-deep/gpu] The company announced that the successor to the RDNA microarchitecture would be incremental (a "refresh").
[src:futhark-deep/gpu] AMD unveiled the Radeon RX 6000 series, its RDNA 2 graphics cards with support for hardware-accelerated ray tracing.
[src:futhark-deep/gpu] The product series, launched in late 2020, consisted of the RX 6800, RX 6800 XT, and RX 6900 XT.
[src:futhark-deep/gpu] The RX 6700 XT, which is based on Navi 22, was launched in early 2021.
[src:futhark-deep/gpu] The PlayStation 5 and Xbox Series X and Series S were released in 2020; they both use GPUs based on the RDNA 2 microarchitecture with incremental improvements and different GPU configurations in each system's implementation.
[src:futhark-deep/gpu] In the 2020s, GPUs have been increasingly used for calculations involving embarrassingly parallel problems, such as training of neural networks on enormous datasets that are needed for artificial intelligence large language models.
[src:futhark-deep/gpu] Specialized processing cores on most modern GPUs that are dedicated to deep learning provide significant FLOPS performance increases, using 4×4 matrix multiplication and division.
[src:futhark-deep/gpu] Early implementations, such as Nvidia's Volta microarchitecture, released in 2017, saw results of up to 128 TFLOPS in some applications.
[src:futhark-deep/gpu] Since then, AI acceleration cores have been a widely adopted feature in consumer and workstation microarchitectures starting with Nvidia's Turing microarchitecture in 2018, named Tensor cores.
[src:futhark-deep/gpu] AMD originally implemented their equivalent "Matrix" Cores for consumers in their RDNA 3 architecture - however RDNA 4's Matrix Cores were the first to introduce FP8 acceleration - which is required to run the full FSR Redstone feature set such as Machine Learning Upscaling and Frame Generation.
[src:futhark-deep/gpu] However, community made hacks on both Linux and Windows have allowed RDNA 2, 3, and competitor GPUs to run a weaker version of FSR 4 known as FSR 4 INT8.
[src:futhark-deep/gpu] The PlayStation 5 Pro, launched in 2024, has customized Machine Learning cores - which focus solely on INT8 acceleration - based on RDNA 4's for PlayStation Spectral Super Resolution to enhance framerates and image quality.
[src:futhark-deep/gpu] Intel has implemented their equivalent "XMX" Cores in all of their Arc GPUs, starting with the Alchemist microarchitecture.
[src:futhark-deep/gpu] This is used for XeSS (Xe Super Sampling), XeFG (Xe Frame Generation), and more.
[src:futhark-deep/gpu] Ray tracing has also been incredibly prevalent in the 2020s with some games, such as DOOM: The Dark Ages, requiring a hardware ray tracing capable GPU to even start.
[src:futhark-deep/gpu] While it does lead to worse performance and less overall accessibility, id software claimed this saved several man hours and shrinked the game by over 100 gigabytes due to the game being entirely built around ray tracing .
[src:futhark-deep/gpu] In 2013, 438.3 million GPUs were shipped globally and the forecast for 2014 was 414.2 million.
[src:futhark-deep/gpu] However, by the third quarter of 2022, shipments of PC GPUs totaled around 75.5 million units, down 19% year-over-year.
[src:futhark-deep/parallel-programming-model] In computing, a **parallel programming model** is an abstraction of parallel computer architecture, with which it is convenient to express algorithms and their composition in programs.
[src:futhark-deep/parallel-programming-model] The value of a programming model can be judged on its *generality*: how well a range of different problems can be expressed for a variety of different architectures, and its *performance*: how efficiently the compiled programs can execute.
[src:futhark-deep/parallel-programming-model] The implementation of a parallel programming model can take the form of a library invoked from a programming language, as an extension to an existing languages.
[src:futhark-deep/parallel-programming-model] Consensus around a particular programming model is important because it leads to different parallel computers being built with support for the model, thereby facilitating portability of software.
[src:futhark-deep/parallel-programming-model] In this sense, programming models are referred to as *bridging* between hardware and software.
[src:futhark-deep/parallel-programming-model] Classifications of parallel programming models can be divided broadly into two areas: process interaction and problem decomposition.
[src:futhark-deep/parallel-programming-model] Process interaction relates to the mechanisms by which parallel processes are able to communicate with each other.
[src:futhark-deep/parallel-programming-model] The most common forms of interaction are shared memory and message passing, but interaction can also be implicit (invisible to the programmer).
[src:futhark-deep/parallel-programming-model] Shared memory is an efficient means of passing data between processes.
[src:futhark-deep/parallel-programming-model] In a shared-memory model, parallel processes share a global address space that they read and write to asynchronously.
[src:futhark-deep/parallel-programming-model] Asynchronous concurrent access can lead to race conditions, and mechanisms such as locks, semaphores and monitors can be used to avoid these.
[src:futhark-deep/parallel-programming-model] Conventional multi-core processors directly support shared memory, which many parallel programming languages and libraries, such as Cilk, OpenMP and Threading Building Blocks, are designed to exploit.
[src:futhark-deep/parallel-programming-model] In a message-passing model, parallel processes exchange data through passing messages to one another.
[src:futhark-deep/parallel-programming-model] These communications can be asynchronous, where a message can be sent before the receiver is ready, or synchronous, where the receiver must be ready.
[src:futhark-deep/parallel-programming-model] The Communicating sequential processes (CSP) formalisation of message passing uses synchronous communication channels to connect processes, and led to important languages such as Occam, Limbo and Go.
[src:futhark-deep/parallel-programming-model] In contrast, the actor model uses asynchronous message passing and has been employed in the design of languages such as D, Scala and SALSA.
[src:futhark-deep/parallel-programming-model] Partitioned Global Address Space (PGAS) models provide a middle ground between shared memory and message passing.
[src:futhark-deep/parallel-programming-model] PGAS provides a global memory address space abstraction that is logically partitioned, where a portion is local to each process.
[src:futhark-deep/parallel-programming-model] Parallel processes communicate by asynchronously performing operations (e.g. reads and writes) on the global address space, in a manner reminiscent of shared memory models.
[src:futhark-deep/parallel-programming-model] However by semantically partitioning the global address space into portions with affinity to a particular processes, they allow programmers to exploit locality of reference and enable efficient implementation on distributed memory parallel computers.
[src:futhark-deep/parallel-programming-model] PGAS is offered by many parallel programming languages and libraries, such as Fortran 2008, Chapel, UPC++, and SHMEM.
[src:futhark-deep/parallel-programming-model] In an implicit model, no process interaction is visible to the programmer and instead the compiler and/or runtime is responsible for performing it.
[src:futhark-deep/parallel-programming-model] Two examples of implicit parallelism are with domain-specific languages where the concurrency within high-level operations is prescribed, and with functional programming languages because the absence of side-effects allows non-dependent functions to be executed in parallel.
[src:futhark-deep/parallel-programming-model] However, this kind of parallelism is difficult to manage and functional languages such as Concurrent Haskell and Concurrent ML provide features to manage parallelism explicitly and correctly.
[src:futhark-deep/parallel-programming-model] A parallel program is composed of simultaneously executing processes.
[src:futhark-deep/parallel-programming-model] Problem decomposition relates to the way in which the constituent processes are formulated.
[src:futhark-deep/parallel-programming-model] A task-parallel model focuses on processes, or threads of execution.
[src:futhark-deep/parallel-programming-model] These processes will often be behaviourally distinct, which emphasises the need for communication.
[src:futhark-deep/parallel-programming-model] Task parallelism is a natural way to express message-passing communication.
[src:futhark-deep/parallel-programming-model] In Flynn's taxonomy, task parallelism is usually classified as MIMD/MPMD or MISD.
[src:futhark-deep/parallel-programming-model] A data-parallel model focuses on performing operations on a data set, typically a regularly structured array.
[src:futhark-deep/parallel-programming-model] A set of tasks will operate on this data, but independently on disjoint partitions.
[src:futhark-deep/parallel-programming-model] In Flynn's taxonomy, data parallelism is usually classified as MIMD/SPMD or SIMD.
[src:futhark-deep/parallel-programming-model] Stream parallelism, also known as pipeline parallelism, focuses on dividing a computation into a sequence of stages, where each stage processes a portion of the input data.
[src:futhark-deep/parallel-programming-model] Each stage operates independently and concurrently, and the output of one stage serves as the input to the next stage.
[src:futhark-deep/parallel-programming-model] Stream parallelism is particularly suitable for applications with continuous data streams or pipelined computations.
[src:futhark-deep/parallel-programming-model] As with implicit process interaction, an implicit model of parallelism reveals nothing to the programmer as the compiler, the runtime or the hardware is responsible.
[src:futhark-deep/parallel-programming-model] For example, in compilers, automatic parallelization is the process of converting sequential code into parallel code, and in computer architecture, superscalar execution is a mechanism whereby instruction-level parallelism is exploited to perform operations in parallel.
[src:futhark-deep/parallel-programming-model] Parallel programming models are closely related to models of computation.
[src:futhark-deep/parallel-programming-model] A model of parallel computation is an abstraction used to analyze the cost of computational processes, but it does not necessarily need to be practical, in that it can be implemented efficiently in hardware and/or software.
[src:futhark-deep/parallel-programming-model] A programming model, in contrast, does specifically imply the practical considerations of hardware and software implementation.
[src:futhark-deep/parallel-programming-model] A parallel programming language may be based on one or a combination of programming models.
[src:futhark-deep/parallel-programming-model] For example, High Performance Fortran is based on shared-memory interactions and data-parallel problem decomposition, and Go provides mechanism for shared-memory and message-passing interaction.
[src:futhark-deep/purely-functional-programming] In computer science, **purely functional programming** usually designates a programming paradigm—a style of building the structure and elements of computer programs—that treats all computation as the evaluation of mathematical functions.
[src:futhark-deep/purely-functional-programming] This style handles state changes without losing the referential transparency of the program expressions.
[src:futhark-deep/purely-functional-programming] Purely functional programming consists of ensuring that functions, inside the functional paradigm, will only depend on their arguments, regardless of any global or local state.
[src:futhark-deep/purely-functional-programming] A pure functional subroutine only has visibility of changes of state represented by state variables included in its scope.
[src:futhark-deep/purely-functional-programming] The exact difference between pure and impure functional programming is a matter of controversy.
[src:futhark-deep/purely-functional-programming] Sabry's proposed definition of purity is that all common evaluation strategies (call-by-name, call-by-value, and call-by-need) produce the same result, ignoring strategies that error or diverge.
[src:futhark-deep/purely-functional-programming] A program is usually said to be functional when it uses some concepts of functional programming, such as first-class functions and higher-order functions.
[src:futhark-deep/purely-functional-programming] However, a first-class function need not be purely functional, as it may use techniques from the imperative paradigm, such as arrays or input/output methods that use mutable cells, which update their state as side effects.
[src:futhark-deep/purely-functional-programming] In fact, the earliest programming languages cited as being functional, IPL and Lisp, are both "impure" functional languages by Sabry's definition.
[src:futhark-deep/purely-functional-programming] Each evaluation strategy which ends on a purely functional program returns the same result.
[src:futhark-deep/purely-functional-programming] In particular, it ensures that the programmer does not have to consider in which order programs are evaluated, since eager evaluation will return the same result as lazy evaluation.
[src:futhark-deep/purely-functional-programming] However, it is still possible that an eager evaluation may not terminate while the lazy evaluation of the same program halts.
[src:futhark-deep/purely-functional-programming] An advantage of this is that lazy evaluation can be implemented much more easily; as all expressions will return the same result at any moment (regardless of program state), their evaluation can be delayed as much as necessary.
[src:futhark-deep/purely-functional-programming] In a purely functional language, the only dependencies between computations are data dependencies, and computations are deterministic.
[src:futhark-deep/purely-functional-programming] Therefore, to program in parallel, the programmer need only specify the pieces that should be computed in parallel, and the runtime can handle all other details such as distributing tasks to processors, managing synchronization and communication, and collecting garbage in parallel.
[src:futhark-deep/purely-functional-programming] This style of programming avoids common issues such as race conditions and deadlocks, but has less control than an imperative language.
[src:futhark-deep/purely-functional-programming] To ensure a speedup, the granularity of tasks must be carefully chosen to be neither too big nor too small.
[src:futhark-deep/purely-functional-programming] In theory, it is possible to use runtime profiling and compile-time analysis to judge whether introducing parallelism will speed up the program, and thus automatically parallelize purely functional programs.
[src:futhark-deep/purely-functional-programming] In practice, this has not been terribly successful, and fully automatic parallelization is not practical.
[src:futhark-deep/purely-functional-programming] Purely functional data structures are persistent.
[src:futhark-deep/purely-functional-programming] Persistency is required for functional programming; without it, the same computation could return different results.
[src:futhark-deep/purely-functional-programming] Functional programming may use persistent non-purely functional data structures, while those data structures may not be used in purely functional programs.
[src:futhark-deep/purely-functional-programming] Purely functional data structures are often represented in a different way than their imperative counterparts.
[src:futhark-deep/purely-functional-programming] For example, array with constant-time access and update is a basic component of most imperative languages and many imperative data-structures, such as hash table and binary heap, are based on arrays.
[src:futhark-deep/purely-functional-programming] Arrays can be replaced by map or random access list, which admits purely functional implementation, but the access and update time is logarithmic.
[src:futhark-deep/purely-functional-programming] Therefore, purely functional data structures can be used in languages which are non-functional, but they may not be the most efficient tool available, especially if persistency is not required.
[src:futhark-deep/purely-functional-programming] In general, conversion of an imperative program to a purely functional one also requires ensuring that the formerly-mutable structures are now explicitly returned from functions that update them, a program structure called store-passing style.
[src:futhark-deep/purely-functional-programming] A purely functional language is a language which only admits purely functional programming.
[src:futhark-deep/purely-functional-programming] Purely functional programs can however be written in languages which are not purely functional.
[src:futhark-deep/simd] Such machines exploit data level parallelism, but not concurrency: there are simultaneous (parallel) computations, but each unit performs exactly the same instruction at any given moment (just with different data).
[src:futhark-deep/simd] A simple example is to add many pairs of numbers together, all of the SIMD units are performing an addition, but each one has different pairs of values to add.
[src:futhark-deep/simd] SIMD is especially applicable to common tasks such as adjusting the contrast in a digital image or adjusting the volume of digital audio.
[src:futhark-deep/simd] Most modern central processing unit (CPU) designs include SIMD instructions to improve the performance of multimedia use.
[src:futhark-deep/simd] In recent CPUs, SIMD units are tightly coupled with cache hierarchies and prefetch mechanisms, which minimize latency during large block operations.
[src:futhark-deep/simd] For instance, AVX-512-enabled processors can prefetch entire cache lines and apply fused multiply-add operations (FMA) in a single SIMD cycle.
[src:futhark-deep/simd] SIMD has three different subcategories in Flynn's 1972 Taxonomy, one of which is single instruction, multiple threads (SIMT).
[src:futhark-deep/simd] SIMT should not be confused with software threads or hardware threads, both of which are task time-sharing (time-slicing).
[src:futhark-deep/simd] SIMT is true simultaneous parallel hardware-level execution, such as in the ILLIAC IV.
[src:futhark-deep/simd] SIMD should not be confused with Vector processing, characterized by the Cray 1 and clarified in Duncan's taxonomy.
[src:futhark-deep/simd] The difference between SIMD and vector processors is primarily the presence of a Cray-style `SET VECTOR LENGTH` instruction.
[src:futhark-deep/simd] The first known operational use to date of SIMD within a register was the TX-2, in 1958.
[src:futhark-deep/simd] It was capable of 36-bit operations and two 18-bit or four 9-bit sub-word operations.
[src:futhark-deep/simd] The first commercial use of SIMD instructions was in the ILLIAC IV, which was completed in 1972.
[src:futhark-deep/simd] Vector supercomputers of the early 1970s such as the CDC Star-100 and the Texas Instruments ASC could operate on a "vector" of data with a single instruction.
[src:futhark-deep/simd] Vector processing was especially popularized by Cray in the 1970s and 1980s.
[src:futhark-deep/simd] Vector processing architectures are now considered separate from SIMD computers: Duncan's Taxonomy includes them whereas Flynn's Taxonomy does not, due to Flynn's work (1966, 1972) pre-dating the Cray-1 (1977).
[src:futhark-deep/simd] The complexity of Vector processors however inspired a simpler arrangement known as SIMD within a register.
[src:futhark-deep/simd] The first era of modern SIMD computers was characterized by massively parallel processing-style supercomputers such as the Thinking Machines Connection Machine CM-1 and CM-2.
[src:futhark-deep/simd] These computers had many limited-functionality processors that would work in parallel.
[src:futhark-deep/simd] For example, each of 65,536 single-bit processors in a Thinking Machines CM-2 would execute the same instruction at the same time, allowing, for instance, to logically combine 65,536 pairs of bits at a time, using a hypercube-connected network or processor-dedicated RAM to find its operands.
[src:futhark-deep/simd] Supercomputing moved away from the SIMD approach when inexpensive scalar multiple instruction, multiple data (MIMD) approaches based on commodity processors such as the Intel i860 XP became more powerful, and interest in SIMD waned.
[src:futhark-deep/simd] The current era of SIMD processors grew out of the desktop-computer market rather than the supercomputer market.
[src:futhark-deep/simd] As desktop processors became powerful enough to support real-time gaming and audio/video processing during the 1990s, demand grew for this type of computing power, and microprocessor vendors turned to SIMD to meet the demand.
[src:futhark-deep/simd] This resurgence also coincided with the rise of DirectX and OpenGL shader models, which heavily leveraged SIMD under the hood.
[src:futhark-deep/simd] The graphics APIs encouraged programmers to adopt data-parallel programming styles, indirectly accelerating SIMD adoption in desktop software.
[src:futhark-deep/simd] Hewlett-Packard introduced Multimedia Acceleration eXtensions (MAX) instructions into PA-RISC 1.1 desktops in 1994 to accelerate MPEG decoding.
[src:futhark-deep/simd] Sun Microsystems introduced SIMD integer instructions in its "VIS" instruction set extensions in 1995, in its UltraSPARC I microprocessor.
[src:futhark-deep/simd] MIPS followed suit with their similar MDMX system.
[src:futhark-deep/simd] The first widely deployed desktop SIMD was with Intel's MMX extensions to the x86 architecture in 1996.
[src:futhark-deep/simd] This sparked the introduction of the much more powerful AltiVec system in the Motorola PowerPC and IBM's POWER systems.
[src:futhark-deep/simd] Intel responded in 1999 by introducing the all-new SSE system.
[src:futhark-deep/simd] Since then, there have been several extensions to the SIMD instruction sets for both architectures.
[src:futhark-deep/simd] Advanced vector extensions AVX, AVX2 and AVX-512 are developed by Intel.
[src:futhark-deep/simd] AMD supports AVX, AVX2, and AVX-512 in their current products.
[src:futhark-deep/simd] With SIMD, an order of magnitude increase in code size is not uncommon, when compared to equivalent scalar or equivalent vector code, and an order of magnitude *or greater* effectiveness (work done per instruction) is achievable with Vector ISAs.
[src:futhark-deep/simd] ARM's Scalable Vector Extension takes another approach, known in Flynn's Taxonomy more commonly known today as "Predicated" (masked) SIMD.
[src:futhark-deep/simd] This approach is not as compact as vector processing but is still far better than non-predicated SIMD.
[src:futhark-deep/simd] Detailed comparative examples are given at Vector processor § Vector instruction example.
[src:futhark-deep/simd] Small-scale (64 or 128 bits) SIMD became popular on general-purpose CPUs in the early 1990s and continued through 1997 and later with Motion Video Instructions (MVI) for Alpha.
[src:futhark-deep/simd] Intel's AVX-512 SIMD instructions process 512 bits of data at once.
[src:futhark-deep/simd] The IBM, Sony, Toshiba co-developed Cell processor's Synergistic Processing Element's (SPE's) instruction set is heavily SIMD based.
[src:futhark-deep/simd] AMD GPUs since the TeraScale (microarchitecture) are SIMD-based, a feature that has remained in the 2020s microartectures RDNA and CDNA, with a layer of single instruction, multiple threads (SIMT) above.
[src:futhark-deep/simd] On the other hand, Nvidia's CUDA architectures use scalar cores with SIMT.
[src:futhark-deep/simd] Philips, now NXP, developed several SIMD processors named Xetal.
[src:futhark-deep/simd] The Xetal has 320 16-bit processor elements especially designed for vision tasks.
[src:futhark-deep/simd] Apple's M1 and M2 chips also incorporate SIMD units deeply integrated with their GPU and Neural Engine, using Apple-designed SIMD pipelines optimized for image filtering, convolution, and matrix multiplication.
[src:futhark-deep/simd] This unified memory architecture helps SIMD instructions operate on shared memory pools more efficiently.
[src:futhark-deep/simd] (The CPU part implements ordinary NEON).
[src:futhark-deep/simd] SIMD instructions are widely used to process 3D graphics, although modern graphics cards with embedded SIMD have largely taken over this task from the CPU.
[src:futhark-deep/simd] Some systems also include permute functions that re-pack elements inside vectors, making them especially useful for data processing and compression.
[src:futhark-deep/simd] The trend of general-purpose computing on GPUs (GPGPU) may lead to wider use of SIMD in the future.
[src:futhark-deep/simd] Recent compilers such as LLVM, GNU Compiler Collection (GCC), and Intel's ICC offer aggressive auto-vectoring options.
[src:futhark-deep/simd] Developers can often enable these with flags like `-O3` or `-ftree-vectorize`, which guide the compiler to restructure loops for SIMD compatibility.
[src:futhark-deep/simd] Adoption of SIMD systems in personal computer software was at first slow, due to a number of problems.
[src:futhark-deep/simd] One was that many of the early SIMD instruction sets tended to slow overall performance of the system due to the re-use of existing floating point registers.
[src:futhark-deep/simd] Other systems, like MMX and 3DNow!, offered support for data types that were not interesting to a wide audience and had expensive context switching instructions to switch between using the FPU and MMX registers.
[src:futhark-deep/simd] Compilers also often lacked support, requiring programmers to resort to assembly language coding.
[src:futhark-deep/simd] The introduction of 3DNow! by AMD and SSE by Intel confused matters somewhat, but today the system seems to have settled down (after AMD adopted SSE) and newer compilers should result in more SIMD-enabled software.
[src:futhark-deep/simd] Intel and AMD now both provide optimized math libraries that use SIMD instructions, and open source alternatives like libSIMD, SIMDx86 and SLEEF have started to appear (see also libm).
[src:futhark-deep/simd] Apple Computer had somewhat more success, even though they entered the SIMD market later than the rest.
[src:futhark-deep/simd] AltiVec offered a rich system and can be programmed using increasingly sophisticated compilers from Motorola, IBM and GNU, therefore assembly language programming is rarely needed.
[src:futhark-deep/simd] Additionally, many of the systems that would benefit from SIMD were supplied by Apple itself, for example iTunes and QuickTime.
[src:futhark-deep/simd] However, in 2006, Apple computers moved to Intel x86 processors.
[src:futhark-deep/simd] Apple's APIs and development tools (XCode) were modified to support SSE2 and SSE3 as well as AltiVec.
[src:futhark-deep/simd] Apple was the dominant purchaser of PowerPC chips from IBM and Freescale Semiconductor.
[src:futhark-deep/simd] Even though Apple has stopped using PowerPC processors in their products, further development of AltiVec is continued in several PowerPC and Power ISA designs from Freescale and IBM.
[src:futhark-deep/simd] It is common for publishers of the SIMD instruction sets to make their own C and C++ language extensions with intrinsic functions or special datatypes (with operator overloading) guaranteeing the generation of vector code.
[src:futhark-deep/simd] Intel, AltiVec, and ARM NEON provide extensions widely adopted by the compilers targeting their CPUs.
[src:futhark-deep/simd] The GNU C Compiler takes the extensions a step further by abstracting them into a universal interface that can be used on any platform by providing a way of defining SIMD datatypes.
[src:futhark-deep/simd] The LLVM Clang compiler also implements the feature, with an analogous interface defined in the IR.
[src:futhark-deep/simd] Rust's `packed_simd` crate (and the experimental `std::simd`) uses this interface, and so does Swift 2.0+.
[src:futhark-deep/simd] C++ has an experimental interface `std::experimental::simd` that works similarly to the GCC extension.
[src:futhark-deep/simd] For GCC and libstdc++, a wrapper library that builds on top of the GCC extension is available.
[src:futhark-deep/simd] The `System.Numerics.Vector` package, available on NuGet, implements SIMD datatypes.
[src:futhark-deep/simd] Java also has a new proposed API for SIMD instructions available in OpenJDK 17 in an incubator module.
[src:futhark-deep/simd] It also has a safe fallback mechanism on unsupported CPUs to simple loops.
[src:futhark-deep/simd] Instead of providing an SIMD datatype, compilers can also be hinted to auto-vectorize some loops, potentially taking some assertions about the lack of data dependency.
[src:futhark-deep/simd] This is not as flexible as manipulating SIMD variables directly, but is easier to use.
[src:futhark-deep/simd] OpenMP 4.0+ has a `#pragma omp simd` hint.
[src:futhark-deep/simd] This OpenMP interface has replaced a wide set of nonstandard extensions, including Cilk's `#pragma simd`, GCC's `#pragma GCC ivdep`, and many more.
[src:futhark-deep/simd] "SIMD everywhere", a collection of C/C++ headers implementing platform-specific intrinsics for other platforms (e.g.
[src:futhark-deep/simd] SSE intrinsics for ARM NEON), includes the use of platform-specific intrinsics, generic vector interfaces, and vectorization hints.
[src:futhark-deep/simd] It can be used as a "Rosetta Stone" for comparing these different SIMD programming paradigms.
[src:futhark-deep/simd] Another approach is SPMD: write a program that looks as if it operates only one element on the time, then have a compiler widen it to match the SIMD vector width.
[src:futhark-deep/simd] This is the approach used by graphics shaders and more recently adopted by CPU-oriented tools such as Intel IPSC.
[src:futhark-deep/simd] Consumer software is typically expected to work on a range of CPUs covering multiple generations, which could limit the programmer's ability to use new SIMD instructions to improve the computational performance of a program.
[src:futhark-deep/simd] The solution is to include multiple versions of the same code that uses either older or newer SIMD technologies, and pick one that best fits the user's CPU at run-time (dynamic dispatch).
[src:futhark-deep/simd] FMV, manually coded in assembly language, is quite commonly used in a number of performance-critical libraries such as glibc and libjpeg-turbo.
[src:futhark-deep/simd] Intel C++ Compiler, GNU Compiler Collection since GCC 6, and Clang since clang 7 allow for a simplified approach, with the compiler taking care of function duplication and selection.
[src:futhark-deep/simd] GCC and clang requires explicit `target_clones` labels in the code to "clone" functions, while ICC does so automatically (under the command-line option `/Qax`).
[src:futhark-deep/simd] The Rust programming language also supports FMV.
[src:futhark-deep/simd] The setup is similar to GCC and Clang in that the code defines what instruction sets to compile for, but cloning is manually done via inlining.
[src:futhark-deep/simd] As using FMV requires code modification on GCC and Clang, vendors more commonly use library multi-versioning: this is easier to achieve as only compiler switches need to be changed.
[src:futhark-deep/simd] Glibc supports LMV and this functionality is adopted by the Intel-backed Clear Linux project.
[src:futhark-deep/simd] In 2013 John McCutchan announced that he had created a high-performance interface to SIMD instruction sets for the Dart programming language, bringing the benefits of SIMD to web programs for the first time.
[src:futhark-deep/simd] Instances of these types are immutable and in optimized code are mapped directly to SIMD registers.
[src:futhark-deep/simd] Operations expressed in Dart typically are compiled into a single instruction without any overhead.
[src:futhark-deep/simd] This is similar to C and C++ intrinsics.
[src:futhark-deep/simd] Benchmarks for 4×4 matrix multiplication, 3D vertex transformation, and Mandelbrot set visualization show near 400% speedup compared to scalar code written in Dart.
[src:futhark-deep/simd] Intel announced at IDF 2013 that they were implementing McCutchan's specification for both V8 and SpiderMonkey.
[src:futhark-deep/simd] However, by 2017, SIMD.js was taken out of the ECMAScript standard queue in favor of pursuing a similar interface in WebAssembly.
[src:futhark-deep/simd] Support for SIMD was added to the WebAssembly 2.0 specification, which was finished on 2022 and became official in December 2024.
[src:futhark-deep/simd] LLVM's autovectoring, when compiling C or C++ to WebAssembly, can target WebAssembly SIMD to automatically make use of SIMD, while SIMD intrinsic are also available.
[src:futhark-deep/simd] It has generally proven difficult to find sustainable commercial applications for SIMD-only processors in general-purpose computing.
[src:futhark-deep/simd] One that has had some measure of success is the GAPP, which was developed by Lockheed Martin and taken to the commercial sector by their spin-off Teranex.
[src:futhark-deep/simd] A more ubiquitous application for SIMD is found in video games: nearly every modern video game console since 1998 has incorporated a SIMD processor somewhere in its architecture.
[src:futhark-deep/simd] The PlayStation 2 was unusual in that one of its vector-float units could function as an autonomous digital signal processor (DSP) executing its own instruction stream, or as a coprocessor driven by ordinary CPU instructions.
[src:futhark-deep/simd] 3D graphics applications tend to lend themselves well to SIMD processing as they rely heavily on operations with 4-dimensional vectors.
[src:futhark-deep/simd] Microsoft's Direct3D 9.0 now chooses at runtime processor-specific implementations of its own math operations, including the use of SIMD-capable instructions.
[src:futhark-deep/simd] A later processor that used vector processing is the Cell processor used in the PlayStation 3, which was developed by IBM in cooperation with Toshiba and Sony.
[src:futhark-deep/simd] It uses a number of SIMD processors (a non-uniform memory access (NUMA) architecture, each with independent local store and controlled by a general purpose CPU) and is geared towards the huge datasets required by 3D and video processing applications.
[src:futhark-deep/simd] It differs from traditional ISAs by being SIMD from the ground up with no separate scalar registers.
[src:futhark-deep/simd] Ziilabs produced an SIMD type processor for use on mobile devices, such as media players and mobile phones.
[src:futhark-deep/simd] Larger scale commercial SIMD processors are available from ClearSpeed Technology, Ltd. and Stream Processors, Inc.
[src:futhark-deep/simd] ClearSpeed's CSX600 (2004) has 96 cores each with two double-precision floating point units while the CSX700 (2008) has 192.
[src:futhark-deep/simd] Stream Processors is headed by computer architect Bill Dally.
[src:futhark-deep/simd] Their Storm-1 processor (2007) contains 80 SIMD cores controlled by a MIPS CPU.
